definition.value: A diverse group of pharmacologically active secondary metabolite characteristic to Cannabis plant as well as produced naturally in the body by humans and animals. Cannabinoids contain oxygen as a part of the heterocyclic ring or in the form of various functional groups. They are subdivided on the basis of their origin.
A dipeptide that is the N-acetyl derivative of carnosine.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is salicylic acid substituted by an amino group at the 5-position.
A member of the class of guanidines that is biguanide the carrying two methyl substituents at position 1.
A member of the class of amphetamines in which the amino group of (S)-amphetamine carries a methyl substituent.

A member of the class of ethylenediamine derivatives that is ethylenediamine in which one of the nitrogens is substituted by two methyl groups, and the other nitrogen is substituted by a 2-pyridyl group and a (2-thienyl)methyl group.
A glutamyl-L-amino acid having L-isoleucine as the L-amino acid component.
A monomethylxanthine having the methyl group located at the 1-position. It is a metabolite of caffeine in humans.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is adipic acid substituted with a methyl group at position C-3.
An N-acetyl-amino acid that is tyrosine with an amine hydrogen substituted by an acetyl group.
An O-acylcarnitine compound having adipoyl as the acyl substituent.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as (2E)-3-phenylprop-2-enoyl (cinnamoyl).
An N-alkylpyrrolidine that consists of N-methylpyrrolidinone bearing a pyridin-3-yl substituent at position C-5 (the 5S-enantiomer). It is an alkaloid commonly found in Nicotiana tabacum.
A glutamyl-L-amino acid that is the N-(L-gamma-glutamyl) derivative of L-leucine.
The 6alpha-stereoisomer of  6-methylprednisolone.
A propanolamine that is 1-(propan-2-ylamino)propan-2-ol substituted by a  4-(2-methoxyethyl)phenoxy group at position 1.

A member of the class of imidazoles substituted at C-1, -2 and -5 with 2-hydroxyethyl, nitro and methyl groups respectively. It has activity against anaerobic bacteria and protozoa, and has a radiosensitising effect on hypoxic tumour cells. It may be given by mouth in tablets, or as the benzoate in an oral suspension. The hydrochloride salt can be used in intravenous infusions. Metronidazole is a prodrug and is selective for anaerobic bacteria due to their ability to intracellularly reduce the nitro group of metronidazole to give nitroso-containing intermediates. These can covalently bind to DNA, disrupting its helical structure, inducing DNA strand breaks and inhibiting bacterial nucleic acid synthesis, ultimately resulting in bacterial cell death.

An L-tyrosine derivative that consists of L-tyrosine bearing an additional methyl substituent at position 2. An inhibitor of the enzyme tyrosine 3-monooxygenase, and consequently of the synthesis of catecholamines. It is used to control the symptoms of excessive sympathetic stimulation in patients with pheochromocytoma.
An aromatic ether which is 2,6-dimethylphenyl ether of 2-aminopropan-1-ol.

A racemate composed of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-miconazole. Used (as its nitrate salt) to treat skin infections such as athlete's foot, jock itch, ringworm and other fungal skin infections. It inhibits the synthesis of ergosterol, a critical component of fungal cell membranes.
A dipeptide consisting of L-proline having a glycyl residue attached to its alpha-amino group.

An aromatic amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 2-{[(4-{N'-[(hexyloxy)carbonyl]carbamimidoyl}phenyl)amino]methyl}-1-methyl-1H-benzimidazole-5-carboxylic acid with the secondary amino group of ethyl N-pyridin-2-yl-beta-alaninate. A prodrug for dabigatran, a thrombin inhibitor and anticoagulant which is used for the prevention of stroke and systemic embolism.
An O-acylcarnitine compound having hexanoyl as the acyl substituent.
A N(2)-acylglutamine that has indol-3-ylacetyl as the acyl group.
An O-methylglutarylcarnitine compound having 3-methylglutaryl as the acyl substituent.
A methylhistidine in which the methyl group is located at N-1.
A methylhistidine in which the methyl group is located at N-3.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as isobutryl.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as isovaleryl.
A cephalotaxine-derived alkaloid ester obtained from Cephalotaxus harringtonia; used for the treatment of chronic or accelerated phase chronic myeloid leukaemia.
An O-acylcarnitine compound having trans-2-methyl-2-butenoyl (tiglyl) as the acyl substituent.
An N-alkylpyrrolidine that is cotinine substituted at position C-3 by a hydroxy group (the 3R,5S-diastereomer).
A quinolinemonocarboxylate that is the conjugate base of xanthurenic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A pyrimidine that is 5-(pyrimidin-2-yl}amino-2-methylbenzenesulfonamide substituted at position 4 by a (2,3-dimethylindazol-6-yl)(methyl)amino group. Used as its hydrochloride salt for treatment of kidney cancer.
An imidazolidine-2,4-dione that is hydantoin substituted at position 1 by a [(5-nitro-2-furyl)methylene]amino group. An antibiotic that damages bacterial DNA.
A synthetic glucocorticoid that is the 16,17-acetonide of triamcinolone. Used to treat various skin infections.
An N-(long-chain-acyl)ethanolamine that is the ethanolamide of palmitic (hexadecanoic) acid.
An N-(long-chain-acyl)ethanolamine that is the ethanolamide of oleic acid. The monounsaturated analogue of the endocannabinoid anandamide.
A methyl-branched fatty acyl-CoA obtained from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (E)-isoheptadec-2-enoic acid.

A pyrazolopyridine that is 7-oxo-4,5,6,7-tetrahydro-1H-pyrazolo[3,4-c]pyridine-3-carboxamide substituted at position 1 by a 4-methoxyphenyl group and at position 6 by a 4-(2-oxopiperidin-1-yl)phenyl group. It is used for the prevention and treatment of thromboembolic diseases.
An alkyl,acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl or acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain a total of 32 carbons and 1 double bond.
An alkyl,acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl or acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain a total of 40 carbons and 2 double bonds.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 32 with 0 double bonds.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 34 with 1 double bond.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 38 with 3 double bonds.
A HETE that is (5Z,8Z,12E,14Z)-icosa-5,8,12,14-tetraenoic acid substituted at position 11 by a hydroxy group.
A HODE that consists of 9Z,11E-octadecadienoic acid carrying a 13-hydroxy substituent.
